:[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Warren","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Warin</i>, <i>Werin</i>, a borrowing of ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. Compare   Waring  .","English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from La Varrenne in Seine-Maritime, France, named with a Gaulish element probably descriptive of alluvial land or sandy soil. This was the name of a major Norman family after the Conquest. In Ireland, this name has been Gaelicized as <b>Bharain</b>.","Irish: adopted as an English form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b> (see   Murnane  ,   Warner  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Warrens","meanings":["English: variant of   Warren   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Warrener","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>warrennier</i> ‘warrener’, an officer employed to watch over game in a park or game preserve. Compare   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Murnane","meanings":["Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b>, a shortened and dissimilated form of <b>Ó Manannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Manannán</i>’, name borne in Celtic mythology by a sea god associated with the Isle of Man. All three syllables appear in the variant <b>Marrinan</b>. This name has also been Anglicized as   Warren   and   Warner  ."]},{"name":"Waren","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Warne","meanings":["shortened form of   Warren  .","occasionally a habitational name from Wearne in Somerset. The place takes its name from a lost stream-name based on British <i>verno-</i> ‘alder, swamp’.","English:"]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"(aka","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Masao, Takashi, Kaoru, Makiko, Masahiko, Rieko, Shigeki, Shogo, Akio, Atsuhiko, Atsushi, Haruo.","Japanese: written 岡 or 丘 ‘hill’. It is found mostly in western Japan. In North America, the name could also be a shortening of longer names beginning with <i>Oka-</i>.","Albanian: metonymic occupational name from <i>okë</i> (definite form <i>oka</i>) ‘oke’, the name of an old measure of weight."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Maud  , the usual spelling of the name in North America."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maude de Warren (aka Blauminster) was born in 1235, in Madresfield, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Robert de Braci. She was buried in Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1235–UNKNOWN":"1235–Surnud","1198–1220":"1198–1220","1225–1289":"1225–1289","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1289":"1289","1220":"1220","1198":"1198","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Madresfield, Worcestershire, England":"Madresfield, Worces